1. Why Pagination and Sorting?

Pagination: Breaks large result sets into smaller chunks (pages), making data retrieval
efficient and user-friendly.
Sorting: Orders results by one or more fields (ascending or descending).

2. Key Interfaces and Classes

a. Pageable
Represents pagination information (page number, page size, sorting).
Used as a parameter in repository methods.

Type: Interface
Purpose: Represents pagination information (page number, page size, sorting).
Usage: Used as a parameter in repository methods to request a specific page of data.

Ex:

Pageable pageable = PageRequest.of(0, 10); // First page, 10 items per page

Info:
In the statement:

PageRequest.of(0, 10)
0 is the first page (page numbers start from 0 in Spring Data JPA).
10 is the page size, meaning 10 items per page.
So, if you have 50 users in your database and you use PageRequest.of(0, 10), you will get the first 10 users.
If you use PageRequest.of(1, 10), you will get the next 10 users (users 11–20), and so on.

b. Page
Represents a single page of results, including content, total pages, total elements, etc.
Type: Interface
Purpose: Represents a single page of results, including:
The content (list of entities)
Total pages
Total elements
Current page info
Usage: Returned by repository methods when you use Pageable.

Ex:
Page<User> page = userRepository.findAll(pageable);
List<User> users = page.getContent();
int totalPages = page.getTotalPages();
long totalElements = page.getTotalElements();

c. Sort
Represents sorting information (field, direction).
Type: Class
Purpose: Represents sorting information (field, direction: ASC/DESC).
Usage: Used as a parameter in repository methods or combined with PageRequest for
paginated and sorted results.

Ex:

Sort sort = Sort.by(Sort.Direction.ASC, "name");
List<User> users = userRepository.findAll(sort);

3. Implementing Pagination

Theory
You use Pageable to specify which page and how many items per page you want.
Repository methods return a Page<T> object.

Implementation
Repository Example:

public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
    Page<User> findByStatus(Status status, Pageable pageable);
}

Service Example:

import org.springframework.data.domain.Page;
import org.springframework.data.domain.PageRequest;

Page<User> page = userRepository.findByStatus(Status.ACTIVE, PageRequest.of(0, 10));
// 0 = first page, 10 = page size
List<User> users = page.getContent();
int totalPages = page.getTotalPages();
long totalElements = page.getTotalElements();


4. Implementing Sorting

Theory
Use the Sort class to specify sorting by field(s) and direction (ASC/DESC).

Implementation
Repository Example:

List<User> findAll(Sort sort);

Service Example:

import org.springframework.data.domain.Sort;

List<User> users = userRepository.findAll(Sort.by(Sort.Direction.ASC, "name"));
List<User> usersDesc = userRepository.findAll(Sort.by(Sort.Direction.DESC, "age"));


5. Combining Pagination and Sorting

Theory
You can combine both by passing sorting info to the PageRequest (which implements Pageable).

Implementation
Service Example:

import org.springframework.data.domain.PageRequest;
import org.springframework.data.domain.Sort;

PageRequest pageRequest = PageRequest.of(0, 10, Sort.by("name").descending());
Page<User> page = userRepository.findByStatus(Status.ACTIVE, pageRequest);
List<User> users = page.getContent();


6. Custom Repository Methods

You can use pagination and sorting in custom queries:

Ex:

@Query("SELECT u FROM User u WHERE u.status = :status")
Page<User> findActiveUsers(@Param("status") Status status, Pageable pageable);

